'''''Revolution '76''''' is a 1989 simulation/strategy game by Britannica Software designed for [[Apple IIGS]] and [[IBM PC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://teachersinstitute.yale.edu/curriculum/units/1997/2/97.02.01.x.html|title=97.02.01: Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of Happiness|website=teachersinstitute.yale.edu}}</ref> The game was written by former [[Sid Meier]] colleague, Ed Bever.<ref>https://www.nikopik.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Inserez-la-disquette-2.pdf {{Bare URL PDF|date=March 2022}}</ref> The title is a simulation of the economic, social and political conditions at the commencement of the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/122407194/|title=Arizona Republic from Phoenix, Arizona on December 2, 1990 Â· Page 89|date=2 December 1990 |publisher=}}</ref>

==Reception==
[[ACE (games magazine)|''Ace magazine'']] felt the game was both complex and manageable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/ace-magazine-34|title=ACE Magazine Issue 34|date=1 July 1990|publisher=|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> [[Compute!|''Compute magazine'']] thought the title was a recreation of the war couched inside a video game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atarimagazines.com/compute/issue125/73_Learn_and_play_play.php|title=Learn and play, play and learn; games that teach are more fun than ever|first=Classic Computer Magazine|last=Archive|website=www.atarimagazines.com}}</ref> ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' decided that the game offered depth, challenge, and replay value.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Emrich |first=Alan |title=Run For Your Fife: Britannica's "Revolution '76" |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=November 1989 |volume=1 |issue=65 |pages=34 | url = http://pdf.textfiles.com/zines/CGW/1989_11_issue65.pdf}}</ref>

